<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>GR-3 Rational Functions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers rational functions. You should be able to identify the domain and range of a 
      rational function. Be able to determine the vertical, horizontal, and oblique asymptotes of a 
      rational function. You should also be able to find the x-intercepts and y-intercept of a rational 
      function. If a rational function has holes (deleted points), you should be able to identify 
      these as well. You should also be able to determine the behavior of a rational function near 
      the asymptotes and the end behavior of a rational function. You should also be able to graph rational functions.  You should be able to write out complete 
      steps to solve these types of problems by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>End Behavior: Determine the end behavior of a rational function and write this using 
        correct notation.</p></li>
      <li><p>Write the equations of the vertical, horizontal, and oblique asymptotes of a rational function.</p></li>
      <li><p>Write the x-intercepts and the y-intercept of a rational function.</p></li>
      <li><p>Identify any holes (deleted points) of a rational function.</p></li>
       <li><p>Determine the behavior of a rational function near the asymptotes.</p></li>
      <li><p>Graphing: Graph the function with appropriate scales and labels, showing the correct 
        intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>Given the function <m>r(x)=\frac{4x^2}{x^2-2x-3}</m>.</p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the domain. </p></statement>
        <hint><p>Set the denominator equal to zero and solve for x to find the values that 
          are not in the domain.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>(-\infty,-1)\cup(-1,3)\cup(3,\infty)</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>To find the domain, we set the denominator equal to zero and 
            solve for x. We have: <m>x^2-2x-3=0</m>. Factoring, we get <m>(x-3)(x+1)=0</m>. 
            Therefore, <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=-1</m> are not in the domain. The domain is 
            <m>(-\infty,-1)\cup(-1,3)\cup(3,\infty)</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
          <statement><p>State any intercepts and/or asymptotes.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>To find the vertical asymptotes, we look at the values that are not in the domain. 
            To find the horizontal or oblique asymptote, we compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator.</p></hint>
          <answer><p>Vertical asymptotes: x=-1 and x=3. Horizontal asymptote: y=4. 
            x-intercept: (0,0). y-intercept: (0,0).</p></answer>
          <solution><p>To find the vertical asymptotes, we look at the values that are not in the domain. We have vertical 
            asymptotes at <m>x=-1</m> and <m>x=3</m>. To find the horizontal or oblique asymptote, we compare the degrees 
            of the numerator and denominator. The degree of the numerator is 2 and the degree of the denominator is 2. 
            Since the degrees are equal, there is a horizontal asymptote at <m>y=\frac{4}{1}=4</m>. 
            To find the x-intercept, we set the numerator equal to zero and solve for x. We have <m>4x^2=0</m>, 
            which gives us an x-intercept at <m>(0,0)</m>. 
            To find the y-intercept, we evaluate the function at x=0. We have <m>r(0)=\frac{4(0)^2}{(0)^2-2(0)-3}=0</m>, 
            which gives us a y-intercept at <m>(0,0)</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
          <statement><p>State any deleted points.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Deleted points occur when there is a common factor in the numerator and 
            denominator that can be canceled.</p></hint>
          <answer><p>No deleted points.</p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
          <statement><p>Provide a sketch of the graph.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Use the intercepts, asymptotes, and general shape of the graph to sketch it.</p></hint>
          <answer>
              <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-gr3a-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>r(x)=(4*x^2)/(x^2-2*x-3)</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                    <grid spacings="((-10,2,10),(-10,2,10))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="r"/>
                    <point p="(0,0)" alignment="se">(0,0)</point>
                    <line endpoints="((-1,-10),(-1,10))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.3"><m>x=-1</m></line>
                    <line endpoints="((3,10),(3,-10))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.2"><m>x=3</m></line>
                    <line endpoints="((-10,1),(10,1))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.8"><m>y=1</m></line>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                      text="The graph is a rational function separated into three branches by the vertical 
                      asymptotes at x=-1 and x=3. The graph has a horizontal asymptote at y=4. The graph 
                      passes through the origin (0,0) which is both the x-intercept and y-intercept. For x less than -1, 
                      the graph is below the x-axis and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=-1 from below and 
                      approaches the horizontal asymptote at y=4 from below. For -1 less than x less than 3, the graph is 
                      above the x-axis and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=-1 from above and approaches 
                      the vertical asymptote at x=3 from above. For x greater than 3, the graph is above the x-axis and 
                      approaches the vertical asymptote at x=3 from above and approaches the horizontal 
                      asymptote at y=4 from above.">
                          </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </answer>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
           Given the function <m>r(x)=\frac{3x-x^2}{2x-2}</m>.
      </p></introduction>
          <task>
            <statement><p>State the domain. </p></statement>
            <hint><p>Set the denominator equal to zero and solve for x to find the values that 
              are not in the domain.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>(-\infty,1)\cup(1,\infty)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the domain, we set the denominator equal to zero and 
              solve for x. We have: <m>2x-2=0</m>. Solving for x gives us <m>x=1</m>. Therefore, the domain is 
              <m>(-\infty,1)\cup(1,\infty)</m>.</p></solution>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement><p>State any intercepts and/or asymptotes.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the vertical asymptotes, we look at the values that are not in the domain. 
              To find the horizontal or oblique asymptote, we compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>Vertical asymptote: x=1. Oblique asymptote: y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1. 
              x-intercept: (0,0). y-intercept: (0,0).</p></answer>
            <solution><p>We have a vertical asymptote at <m>x=1</m>. To find the oblique asymptote, we perform 
              polynomial long division. The result is <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1</m>. For the intercepts, we 
              set the numerator equal to zero to find the x-intercept and evaluate the function at x=0 to find the 
              y-intercept.</p></solution>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement><p>State any deleted points.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Deleted points occur when there is a common factor in the numerator and 
              denominator that can be canceled.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>No deleted points.</p></answer>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement><p>Provide a sketch of the graph.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the intercepts, asymptotes, and general shape of the graph to sketch it.</p></hint>
            <answer>
              <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-gr3b-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>r(x)=(3*x-x^2)/(2*x-2)</definition>
                  <definition>y=-\frac{1}{2}*x+1</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                    <grid spacings="((-10,2,10),(-10,2,10))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="r"/>
                    <point p="(0,0)" alignment="sw">(0,0)</point>
                    <line endpoints="((1,10),(1,-10))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.8"><m>x=1</m></line>
                    <line endpoints="((-10,6),(10,-4))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.2"><m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1</m></line>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                      text="The graph is a rational function separated into two branches by the vertical 
                      asymptote at x=1. The graph has an oblique asymptote at y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1. The graph 
                      passes through the origin (0,0) which is both the x-intercept and y-intercept. For x less than 1, 
                      the graph is below the oblique asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=1 toward 
                      negative infinity. For 1 greater than x, the graph is above the oblique asymptote and approaches 
                      the vertical asymptote at x=1 toward positive infinity. As x approaches positive or negative 
                      infinity, the graph approaches the oblique asymptote y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1.">
                          </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </answer>
          </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
        Given the function <m>r(x)=\frac{x-2}{-4x^2+6x-2}</m>.
      </p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the domain. </p></statement>
        <hint><p>Set the denominator equal to zero and solve for x to find the values that 
          are not in the domain.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>(-\infty,\frac{1}{2})\cup(\frac{1}{2},1)\cup(1,\infty)</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>To find the domain, we set the denominator equal to zero and 
          solve for x. We have: <m>-4x^2+6x-2=0</m>. Factoring, we get <m>(-2x+1)(2x-2)=0</m>. 
          Therefore, <m>x=\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>x=1</m> are not in the domain. The domain is 
          <m>(-\infty,\frac{1}{2})\cup(\frac{1}{2},1)\cup(1,\infty)</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State any intercepts and/or asymptotes.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the vertical asymptotes, we look at the values that are not in the domain. 
          To find the horizontal or oblique asymptote, we compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>Vertical asymptotes: x=\frac{1}{2} and x=1. Horizontal asymptote: y=0. 
          x-intercept: (2,0). y-intercept: (0,1).</p></answer>
        <solution><p>We have vertical asymptotes at <m>x=\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>x=1</m>. To find the 
          horizontal asymptote, we can see that the degree of the numerator is less than the degree of 
          the denominator. The result is <m>y=0</m>. 
          For the intercepts, we set the numerator equal to zero to find the x-intercept and evaluate the 
          function at x=0 to find the y-intercept.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State any deleted points.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Deleted points occur when there is a common factor in the numerator and 
          denominator that can be canceled.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>No deleted points.</p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Provide a sketch of the graph.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the intercepts, asymptotes, and general shape of the graph to sketch it.</p></hint>
        <answer>
              <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-gr3c-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=(x-2)/(-4*x^2+6*x-2)</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-6,-6,6,6)">
                    <grid spacings="((-6,2,6),(-6,2,6))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f"/>
                    <point p="(0,0)" alignment="sw">(0,0)</point>
                    <line endpoints="((1,-10),(1,10))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.6"><m>x=1</m></line>
                    <line endpoints="((0.5,-10),(0.5,10))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.3"><m>x=0.5</m></line>
                    <line endpoints="((-10,0),(10,0))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.3"><m>y=0</m></line>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                      text="The graph is a rational function separated into three branches by the vertical 
                      asymptotes at x=0.5 and x=1. The graph has an oblique asymptote at y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1. The graph 
                      passes through the y-intercept (0,1)and the x-intercept (2,0). For x less than 0.5, 
                      the graph is above the horizontal asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=0.5 
                      toward positive infinity. For 0.5 less than x less than 1, the graph is below the horizontal asymptote 
                      and approaches both of the vertical asymptotes at x=0.5 and x=1 toward negative infinity. 
                      For x greater than 1, the graph is above the horizontal asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote 
                      at x=1 toward positive infinity. As x approaches positive or negative infinity, the graph 
                      approaches the horizontal asymptote y=0.">
                          </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </answer>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
        Given the function <m>r(x)=\frac{-3x^2-4x+1}{x+1}</m>.
      </p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State the domain. </p></statement>
        <hint><p>Set the denominator equal to zero and solve for x to find the values that 
          are not in the domain.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>(-\infty,-1)\cup(-1,\infty)</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>To find the domain, we set the denominator equal to zero and 
          solve for x. We have: <m>x+1=0</m>. Therefore, <m>x=-1</m> is not in the domain. The domain is 
          <m>(-\infty,-1)\cup(-1,\infty)</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State any intercepts and/or asymptotes.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the vertical asymptotes, we look at the values that are not in the domain. 
          To find the horizontal or oblique asymptote, we compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>No vertical asymptotes. No horizontal or oblique asymptote. 
          x-intercept: (\frac{1}{3},0). y-intercept: (0,-1).</p></answer>
        <solution><p>There are no vertical asymptotes since the only factor in the denominator cancels 
          out with a factor in the numerator. There are also no horizontal or oblique asymptotes because 
          the degree of the numerator is greater than the degree of the denominator.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State any deleted points.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Deleted points occur when there is a common factor in the numerator and 
          denominator that can be canceled.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>The function has a hole at x=-1, which corresponds to the deleted point 
          (-1,2).</p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Provide a sketch of the graph.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the intercepts, asymptotes, and general shape of the graph to sketch it.</p></hint>
        <answer>
              <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-gr3d-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>g(x)=(-3*x-1)</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                    <grid spacings="((-10,2,10),(-10,2,10))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="g"/>
                    <point p="(0,-1)" alignment="w">(0,-1)</point>
                    <point p="(-1/3,0)" alignment="e">(-1/3,0)</point>
                    <circle center="(-1,2)" radius="0.3" fill="white" stroke="blue" alignment="nw"><m>(-1,2)</m></circle>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                      text="The graph is a rational function separated into three branches by the vertical 
                      asymptotes at x=0.5 and x=1. The graph has an oblique asymptote at y=-\frac{1}{2}x+1. The graph 
                      passes through the y-intercept (0,1)and the x-intercept (2,0). For x less than 0.5, 
                      the graph is above the horizontal asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=0.5 
                      toward positive infinity. For 0.5 less than x less than 1, the graph is below the horizontal asymptote 
                      and approaches both of the vertical asymptotes at x=0.5 and x=1 toward negative infinity. 
                      For x greater than 1, the graph is above the horizontal asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote 
                      at x=1 toward positive infinity. As x approaches positive or negative infinity, the graph 
                      approaches the horizontal asymptote y=0.">
                          </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </answer>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
          Given the function <m>r(x)=\frac{x^3+3x^2+6x+8}{x^2-x-6}</m>.
        </p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            State the domain. </p>
          </statement>
          <hint><p>Set the denominator equal to zero and solve for x to find the values that 
            are not in the domain.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>(-\infty,-2)\cup(-2,3)\cup(3,\infty)</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>To find the domain, we set the denominator equal to zero and 
            solve for x. We have: <m>x^2-x-6=0</m>. Factoring, we get <m>(x-3)(x+2)=0</m>. 
            Therefore, <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=3</m> are not in the domain. The domain is 
            <m>(-\infty,-2)\cup(-2,3)\cup(3,\infty)</m>.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State any intercepts and/or asymptotes.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the vertical asymptotes, we look at the values that are not in the 
          domain. To find the horizontal or oblique asymptote, we compare the degrees of the 
          numerator and denominator.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>Vertical asymptote: x=3. Oblique asymptote: y=x+4. 
          x-intercept: none. y-intercept: (0,-\frac{4}{3}).</p></answer>
        <solution><p>We have a vertical asymptote at <m>x=3</m>. To find the 
          oblique asymptote, we perform polynomial long division on the factored form of the function. 
          The result is <m>y=x+4</m>. 
          For the intercepts, we set the numerator equal to zero to find the x-intercept and 
          evaluate the function at x=0 to find the y-intercept.</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>State any deleted points.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Deleted points occur when there is a common factor in the numerator and 
          denominator that can be canceled.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>The function has a hole at x=-2, which corresponds to the point 
          (-2,-\frac{6}{5}).</p></answer>
        <solution><p>To find any deleted points, we look for common factors in the numerator and denominator. 
          We can factor the denominator as <m>(x-3)(x+2)</m>. We can factor the numerator as <m>(x+2)(x^2+x+4)</m>. 
          Therefore, there is a common factor of <m>(x+2)</m> that can be canceled. This means there is a hole 
          at x=-2. To find the y-coordinate of the hole, we can evaluate the function at x=-2 after canceling the 
          common factor. This gives us <m>r(-2)=-\frac{6}{5}</m>. Therefore, the hole is at the point (-2,-\frac{6}{5}).</p></solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Provide a sketch of the graph.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the intercepts, asymptotes, and general shape of the graph to sketch it.</p></hint>
        <answer>
              <image width="60%">
              <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                          label="prefigure-gr3e-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=(x^2+x+4)/(x-3)</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-20,-15,25,30)">
                    <grid spacings="((-20,5,25),(-15,5,30))"/>
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f"/>
                    <point p="(0,-4/3)" alignment="n"><m>(0,-\frac{4}{3})</m></point>
                    <circle center="(-2,-6/5)" radius="0.3" fill="white" stroke="blue" alignment="ne"><m>(-2,-\frac{6}{5})</m></circle>
                    <line endpoints="((3,-15),(3,30))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.8"><m>x=3</m></line>
                    <line endpoints="((25,29),(-20,-16))" stroke="red" dash="4 4" label-location="0.2"><m>y=x+4</m></line>
                  </coordinates>
                  <annotations>
                    <annotation ref="figure"
                      text="The graph is a rational function separated into two branches by the vertical 
                      asymptotes at x=3. The graph has an oblique asymptote at y=x+4. The graph 
                      passes through the y-intercept (0,-\frac{4}{3}). For x is less than 3, 
                      the graph is below the oblique asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=3 
                      toward negative infinity. At x=-2, there is a hole in the graph. For x is greater than 3, the graph 
                      is above the oblique asymptote and approaches the vertical asymptote at x=3 toward
                       positive infinity. As x approaches positive or negative infinity, the graph 
                      approaches the oblique asymptote y=x+4.">
                          </annotation>
                  </annotations>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </answer>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet> 
